"label": Reagents are distinguished from study subjects/evaluants in that study subjects and evaluants are that about which conclusions are drawn and knowledge is sought in an investigation - while reagents
"rel": are not.  It should be noted
column5: that reagent and study subject/evaluant roles can be borne by instances of the same type of material entity - but a given instance will realize only one of these roles in the execution of a given assay or technique. For example
column6: taq polymerase can bear a reagent role or an evaluant role.  In a DNA sequencing assay aimed at generating sequence data about some plasmid
column7: the reagent role of the taq polymerase is realized. In an assay to evaluate the quality of the taq polymerase itself
column8: the evaluant/study subject role of the taq is realized
column9: but not the reagent role since the taq is the subject about which data is generated.

"ent2": dNTPs input into a PCR are reagents that become part of the material output of this technique

By contrast

"label": Reagents are distinguished from study subjects/evaluants in that study subjects and evaluants are that about which conclusions are drawn and knowledge is sought in an investigation - while reagents
"rel": are not.  It should be noted
column5: that reagent and study subject/evaluant roles can be borne by instances of the same type of material entity - but a given instance can only realize one of these roles in the execution of a given  assay. For example
column6: taq polymerase can bear a reagent role or an evaluant role.  In a DNA sequencing assay aimed at generating sequence data about some plasmid
column7: the reagent role of the taq polymerase is realized. In an assay to evaluate the quality of the taq polymerase itself
column8: the evaluant/study subject role of the taq is realized
column9: but not the reagent role since the taq is the subject about which data is generated.

"label": In regard to the statement that reagents are 'distinct' from the specified outputs of a technique:  note that a reagent may be incorporated into a material output of a technique
"ent1": as long as the IDENTITY of this output is distinct from that of the bearer of the reagent role.  For example
"rel": dNTPs input into a PCR are reagents that become part of the material output of this technique
"ent2": but this output has a new identity (ie that of a 'nucleic acid molecule') that is distinct from the identity of the dNTPs that comprise it.  Similarly
column5: a biotin molecule input into a cell labeling technique are reagents that become part of the specified output
column6: but the identity of the output is that of some modified cell specimen which shares identity with the input unmodified cell specimen
column7: and not with the biotin label. Thus
column8: we see that an important criteria of 'reagent-ness' is that it is a facilitator
column9: and not the primary focus of an investigation or material processing technique (ie not the specified subject/evaluant about which knowledge is sought
column10: or the specified output material of the technique)."

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

column7: which tend to settle in roots of the plants within the salt marsh. The natural chemical activity of salty (or brackish) water and the tendency of algae to bloom in the shallow unshaded water also allow for great biodiversity."

"ent2": "PMID: 17601993-Objective: HIV-infected patients with lipodystrophy (HIV-lipodystrophy) are insulin resistant and have elevated plasma free fatty acid (FFA) concentrations. We aimed to explore the mechanisms underlying FFA-induced insulin resistance in patients with HIV-lipodystrophy. Research Design and Methods: Using a randomized placebo-controlled cross-over design
column5: we studied the effects of an overnight acipimox-induced suppression of FFA on glucose and FFA metabolism by using stable isotope labelled tracer techniques during basal conditions and a two-stage euglycemic
column6: hyperinsulinemic clamp (20 mU insulin/m(2)/min; 50 mU insulin/m(2)/min) in nine patients with nondiabetic HIV-lipodystrophy. All patients received antiretroviral therapy. Biopsies from the vastus lateralis muscle were obtained during each stage of the clamp. Results: Acipimox treatment reduced basal FFA rate of appearance by 68.9% (52.6%-79.5%) and decreased plasma FFA concentration by 51.6 % (42.0%-58.9%)
column8: P < 0.0001). Endogenous glucose production was not influenced by acipimox. During the clamp the increase in glucose-uptake was significantly greater after acipimox treatment compared to placebo (acipimox: 26.85 (18.09-39.86) vs placebo: 20.30 (13.67-30.13) mumol/kg/min; P < 0.01). Insulin increased phosphorylation of Akt (Thr(308)) and GSK-3beta (Ser(9))
column9: decreased phosphorylation of glycogen synthase (GS) site 3a+b and increased GS-activity (I-form) in skeletal muscle (P < 0.01). Acipimox decreased phosphorylation of GS (site 3a+b) (P < 0.02) and increased GS-activity (P < 0.01) in muscle. Conclusion: The present study provides direct evidence that suppression of lipolysis in patients with HIV-lipodystrophy improves insulin-stimulated peripheral glucose-uptake. The increased glucose-uptake may in part be explained by increased dephosphorylation of GS (site 3a+b) resulting in increased GS activity."

"ent2": "PMID: 17288613-BSTRACT: BACKGROUND: Physicians in Canadian emergency departments (EDs) annually treat 185
column5: 000 alert and stable trauma victims who are at risk for cervical spine (C-spine) injury. However
column6: only 0.9% of these patients have suffered a cervical spine fracture. Current use of radiography is not efficient. The Canadian C-Spine Rule is designed to allow physicians to be more selective and accurate in ordering C-spine radiography
column7: and to rapidly clear the C-spine without the need for radiography in many patients. The goal of this phase III study is to evaluate the effectiveness of an active strategy to implement the Canadian C-Spine Rule into physician practice. Specific objectives are to: 1) determine clinical impact
column8: 2) determine sustainability
column9: 3) evaluate performance
column10: and 4) conduct an economic evaluation. METHODS: We propose a matched-pair cluster design study that compares outcomes during three consecutive 12-months before
column12: and decay periods at six pairs of intervention and control sites. These 12 hospital ED sites will be stratified as teaching or community hospitals
column13: matched according to baseline C-spine radiography ordering rates
column14: and then allocated within each pair to either intervention or control groups. During the after period at the intervention sites
column15: simple and inexpensive strategies will be employed to actively implement the Canadian C-Spine Rule. The following outcomes will be assessed: 1) measures of clinical impact
column16: 2) performance of the Canadian C-Spine Rule
column17: and 3) economic measures. During the 12-month decay period
column19: allowing us to evaluate the sustainability of the effect. We estimate a sample size of 4
column20: 800 patients in each period in order to have adequate power to evaluate the main outcomes. DISCUSSION: Phase I successfully derived the Canadian C-Spine Rule and phase II confirmed the accuracy and safety of the rule
column22: the potential for physicians to improve care. What remains unknown is the actual change in clinical behaviors that can be affected by implementation of the Canadian C-Spine Rule
column23: and whether implementation can be achieved with simple and inexpensive measures. We believe that the Canadian C-Spine Rule has the potential to significantly reduce health care costs and improve the efficiency of patient flow in busy Canadian EDs."

"ent2": "PMID: 17408389-Purpose: Proliferative vitreoretinopathy (PVR) is the most important reason for blindness following retinal detachment. Presently
column5: vitreous tamponades such as gas or silicone oil cannot contact the lower part of the retina. A heavier-than-water tamponade displaces the inflammatory and PVR-stimulating environment from the inferior area of the retina. The Heavy Silicone Oil versus Standard Silicone Oil Study (HSO Study) is designed to answer the question of whether a heavier-than-water tamponade improves the prognosis of eyes with PVR of the lower retina. Methods: The HSO Study is a multicentre
column7: prospective controlled clinical trial comparing two endotamponades within a two-arm parallel group design. Patients with inferiorly and posteriorly located PVR are randomized to either heavy silicone oil or standard silicone oil as a tamponading agent. Three hundred and fifty consecutive patients are recruited per group. After intraoperative re-attachment
column8: patients are randomized to either standard silicone oil (1000 cSt or 5000 cSt) or Densiron((R)) as a tamponading agent. The main endpoint criteria are complete retinal attachment at 12 months and change of visual acuity (VA) 12 months postoperatively compared with the preoperative VA. Secondary endpoints include complete retinal attachment before endotamponade removal
column9: quality of life analysis and the number of retina affecting re-operation within 1 year of follow-up. Results: The design and early recruitment phase of the study are described. Conclusions: The results of this study will uncover whether or not heavy silicone oil improves the prognosis of eyes with PVR."

"PMID: 17582121-Our objective was to examine the effects of dietary cation-anion difference (DCAD) with different concentrations of dietary crude protein (CP) on performance and acid-base status in early lactation cows. Six lactating Holstein cows averaging 44 d in milk were used in a 6 x 6 Latin square design with a 2 x 3 factorial arrangement of treatments: DCAD of -3
column6: or 47 milliequivalents (Na + K - Cl - S)/100 g of dry matter (DM)
column7: and 16 or 19% CP on a DM basis. Linear increases with DCAD occurred in DM intake
column8: milk fat percentage
column9: 4% fat-corrected milk production
column12: and milk solids-not-fat. Milk production itself was unaffected by DCAD. Jugular venous blood pH
column15: but jugular venous blood Cl- concentration
column17: and net acid excretion decreased linearly with increasing DCAD. An elevated ratio of coccygeal venous plasma essential AA to nonessential AA with increasing DCAD indicated that N metabolism in the rumen was affected
column18: probably resulting in more microbial protein flowing to the small intestine. Cows fed 16% CP had lower urea N in milk than cows fed 19% CP; the same was true for urea N in coccygeal venous plasma and urine. Dry matter intake
column21: and acid-base status did not differ between the 16 and 19% CP treatments. It was concluded that DCAD affected DM intake and performance of dairy cows in early lactation. Feeding 16% dietary CP to cows in early lactation
column22: compared with 19% CP
column23: maintained lactation performance while reducing urea N excretion in milk and urine."

"ent2": "PMID: 17561240-The present experiment evaluates the effects of intermittent exposure to a social stimulus on ethanol and water drinking in rats. Intermittent Social groups received 35 trials per session. Each trial consisted of the insertion of the sipper tube for 10 s followed by lifting of the guillotine door for 15 s. "ent2": "PMID: 14744830-Microarrays are powerful tools for surveying the expression levels of many thousands of genes simultaneously. They belong to the new genomics technologies which have important applications in the biological
column5: agricultural and pharmaceutical sciences. There are myriad sources of uncertainty in microarray experiments
column6: and rigorous experimental design is essential for fully realizing the potential of these valuable resources. Two questions frequently asked by biologists on the brink of conducting cDNA or two-colour
column7: spotted microarray experiments are 'Which mRNA samples should be competitively hybridized together on the same slide?' and 'How many times should each slide be replicated?' Early experience has shown that whilst the field of classical experimental design has much to offer this emerging multi-disciplinary area
column8: new approaches which accommodate features specific to the microarray context are needed. In this paper
column9: we propose optimal designs for factorial and time course experiments
column10: which are special designs arising quite frequently in microarray experimentation. Our criterion for optimality is statistical efficiency based on a new notion of admissible designs; our approach enables efficient designs to be selected subject to the information available on the effects of most interest to biologists
column11: the number of arrays available for the experiment
column12: and other resource or practical constraints
column13: including limitations on the amount of mRNA probe. We show that our designs are superior to both the popular reference designs
column15: and to designs incorporating all possible direct pairwise comparisons. Moreover
column16: our proposed designs represent a substantial practical improvement over classical experimental designs which work in terms of standard interactions and main effects. The latter do not provide a basis for meaningful inference on the effects of most interest to biologists
column17: nor make the most efficient use of valuable and limited resources."

METHODOLOGY: 65 treatment-naove CHC patients who finished a 24-week therapy with peginterferon (alpha-2b (1.5 mcg/kg/week) plus ribavirin (1000-1200 mg /day) and 24 weeks of follow-up were enrolled. Hepatic fibrosis was graded by the METAVIR scoring system. Serum quantitative HCV RNA was determined by Versant HCV RNA 3.0 assay (Bayer Inc.). RESULTS: Genotype non-1 patients responded quickly and a higher percentage of them achieved undetectable HCV RNA (< 615 IU/mL) at week 4 compared with genotype 1 patients (93% vs. 69%
column5: p = 0.018). Degree of hepatic fibrosis significantly affected end-of-treatment and sustained response (SVR). For patients who did not achieve early virological response (EVR)
column6: the negative predictive value for SVR was 100%. In genotype 1 patients
column7: undetectable HCV RNA by week 4 was a good marker to predict treatment response
column8: with a positive predictive value of 84% and a negative predictive value of 82%. CONCLUSIONS: EVR can be applied to Chinese patients as an early stopping rule. A 24-week duration of pegylated IFN/ribavirin might be adequate for genotype 1 patients who rapidly responded to therapy."

"ent2": "PMID: 17601993-Objective: HIV-infected patients with lipodystrophy (HIV-lipodystrophy) are insulin resistant and have elevated plasma free fatty acid (FFA) concentrations. We aimed to explore the mechanisms underlying FFA-induced insulin resistance in patients with HIV-lipodystrophy. Research Design and Methods: Using a randomized placebo-controlled cross-over design
column5: we studied the effects of an overnight acipimox-induced suppression of FFA on glucose and FFA metabolism by using stable isotope labelled tracer techniques during basal conditions and a two-stage euglycemic
column6: hyperinsulinemic clamp (20 mU insulin/m(2)/min; 50 mU insulin/m(2)/min) in nine patients with nondiabetic HIV-lipodystrophy. All patients received antiretroviral therapy. Biopsies from the vastus lateralis muscle were obtained during each stage of the clamp. Results: Acipimox treatment reduced basal FFA rate of appearance by 68.9% (52.6%-79.5%) and decreased plasma FFA concentration by 51.6 % (42.0%-58.9%)
column8: P < 0.0001). Endogenous glucose production was not influenced by acipimox. During the clamp the increase in glucose-uptake was significantly greater after acipimox treatment compared to placebo (acipimox: 26.85 (18.09-39.86) vs placebo: 20.30 (13.67-30.13) mumol/kg/min; P < 0.01). Insulin increased phosphorylation of Akt (Thr(308)) and GSK-3beta (Ser(9))
column9: decreased phosphorylation of glycogen synthase (GS) site 3a+b and increased GS-activity (I-form) in skeletal muscle (P < 0.01). Acipimox decreased phosphorylation of GS (site 3a+b) (P < 0.02) and increased GS-activity (P < 0.01) in muscle. Conclusion: The present study provides direct evidence that suppression of lipolysis in patients with HIV-lipodystrophy improves insulin-stimulated peripheral glucose-uptake. The increased glucose-uptake may in part be explained by increased dephosphorylation of GS (site 3a+b) resulting in increased GS activity."

"ent2": "PMID: 17561240-The present experiment evaluates the effects of intermittent exposure to a social stimulus on ethanol and water drinking in rats. column14: but this effect was not observed with water. Effects of social stimulation on ethanol drinking are discussed."

"ent2": "PMID: 14744830-Microarrays are powerful tools for surveying the expression levels of many thousands of genes simultaneously. They belong to the new genomics technologies which have important applications in the biological
column5: agricultural and pharmaceutical sciences. There are myriad sources of uncertainty in microarray experiments
column6: and rigorous experimental design is essential for fully realizing the potential of these valuable resources. Two questions frequently asked by biologists on the brink of conducting cDNA or two-colour
column7: spotted microarray experiments are 'Which mRNA samples should be competitively hybridized together on the same slide?' and 'How many times should each slide be replicated?' Early experience has shown that whilst the field of classical experimental design has much to offer this emerging multi-disciplinary area
column8: new approaches which accommodate features specific to the microarray context are needed. In this paper
column9: we propose optimal designs for factorial and time course experiments
column10: which are special designs arising quite frequently in microarray experimentation. Our criterion for optimality is statistical efficiency based on a new notion of admissible designs; our approach enables efficient designs to be selected subject to the information available on the effects of most interest to biologists
column11: the number of arrays available for the experiment
column12: and other resource or practical constraints
column13: including limitations on the amount of mRNA probe. We show that our designs are superior to both the popular reference designs
column15: and to designs incorporating all possible direct pairwise comparisons. Moreover
column16: our proposed designs represent a substantial practical improvement over classical experimental designs which work in terms of standard interactions and main effects. The latter do not provide a basis for meaningful inference on the effects of most interest to biologists
column17: nor make the most efficient use of valuable and limited resources."

"ent2": "PMID: 17591081-BACKGROUND/AIMS: To investigate the viral kinetics of Chinese CHC patients received pegylated interferon plus ribavirin and examine the impact of HCV genotypes and severity of liver disease. METHODOLOGY: 65 treatment-naove CHC patients who finished a 24-week therapy with peginterferon (alpha-2b (1.5 mcg/kg/week) plus ribavirin (1000-1200 mg /day) and 24 weeks of follow-up were enrolled. Hepatic fibrosis was graded by the METAVIR scoring system. Serum quantitative HCV RNA was determined by Versant HCV RNA 3.0 assay (Bayer Inc.). RESULTS: Genotype non-1 patients responded quickly and a higher percentage of them achieved undetectable HCV RNA (< 615 IU/mL) at week 4 compared with genotype 1 patients (93% vs. 69%
column5: p = 0.018). Degree of hepatic fibrosis significantly affected end-of-treatment and sustained response (SVR). For patients who did not achieve early virological response (EVR)
column6: the negative predictive value for SVR was 100%. In genotype 1 patients
column7: undetectable HCV RNA by week 4 was a good marker to predict treatment response

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"Debate exists whether a wet meadow is a type of marsh or a completely separate type of wetland. Wet prairies and wet savannas are hydrologically similar. Wet meadows may occur because of restricted drainage or the receipt of large amounts of water from rain or melted snow. They may also occur in riparian zones and around the shores of large lakes. Unlike a marsh or swamp
"ent1": a wet meadow does not have standing water present except for brief to moderate periods during the growing season. Instead
"rel": the ground in a wet meadow fluctuates between brief periods of inundation and longer periods of saturation. Wet meadows often have large numbers of wetland plant species
"ent2": which frequently survive as buried seeds during dry periods
column5: and then regenerate after flooding. Wet meadows therefore do not usually support aquatic life such as fish. They typically have a high diversity of plant species
column6: and may attract large numbers of birds
column7: small mammals and insects including butterflies."
column8: "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01000449"
column9: "http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type"

Reagents are distinguished from instruments or devices that also participate in scientific techniques by the fact that reagents are chemical or biological in nature and necessarily participate in or have parts that participate in some chemical interaction or reaction during their intended participation in some technique.  By contrast
"ent1": instruments do not participate in a chemical reaction/interaction during the technique.

"label": Reagents are distinguished from study subjects/evaluants in that study subjects and evaluants are that about which conclusions are drawn and knowledge is sought in an investigation - while reagents
"rel": are not.  It should be noted
column5: that reagent and study subject/evaluant roles can be borne by instances of the same type of material entity - but a given instance will realize only one of these roles in the execution of a given assay or technique. For example
column6: taq polymerase can bear a reagent role or an evaluant role.  In a DNA sequencing assay aimed at generating sequence data about some plasmid
column7: the reagent role of the taq polymerase is realized. In an assay to evaluate the quality of the taq polymerase itself
column8: the evaluant/study subject role of the taq is realized
column9: but not the reagent role since the taq is the subject about which data is generated.

"label": In regard to the statement that reagents are 'distinct' from the specified outputs of a technique
"ent1": note that a reagent may be incorporated into a material output of a technique
"rel": as long as the IDENTITY of this output is distinct from that of the bearer of the reagent role.  For example
"ent2": dNTPs input into a PCR are reagents that become part of the material output of this technique
column5: but this output has a new identity (ie that of a 'nucleic acid molecule') that is distinct from the identity of the dNTPs that comprise it.  Similarly
column6: a biotin molecule input into a cell labeling technique are reagents that become part of the specified output
column7: but the identity of the output is that of some modified cell specimen which shares identity with the input unmodified cell specimen
column8: and not with the biotin label. Thus
column9: we see that an important criteria of 'reagent-ness' is that it is a facilitator
column10: and not the primary focus of an investigation or material processing technique (ie not the specified subject/evaluant about which knowledge is sought
column11: or the specified output material of the technique)."

"label": "The concept of a 'secondary cultured cell population' covers cell lines as well as cultured cell populations more immediately derived from a primary culture which have yet to achieve adequate genetic stability and compositional homogeneity to be considered a cell line. The extent of the collection of cells in a 'secondary cultured cell population' is restricted only in that all cell members must share a propagation history (ie be derived through a common lineage of passages from an initial culture).  Secondary cultured cell populations can be under active culture
"ent1": stored in a quiescent state for future use

column6: "The term 'secondary cell culture' is generally used in biological texts/protocols to refer to any culture of cells following an initial passage.  We include it here because there are often a number of passages between a primary culture and the establishment of a stable
column7: homogenous cell line.  Such cultures are considered to be 'secondary cultures' but not 'cell lines' during this intermediate passaging/selection period between their derivation from a 'primary cell culture' and derivation into a 'cell line'
column8: which is a more specific type of secondary culture."

"label": "1. The term 'line' is used when a culture has undergone an intentional experimental process to establish a more uniform and stable population of cells (see 'establishing cell line'). This will require one or more passages
"ent1": but may involve additional selection processes. Through such passaging and/or selection processes
"rel": the resulting 'line' attains some level of genetic stability and compositional homogeneity which is typically absent in primary cultures. Because of their relative homogeneity
"ent2": 'lines' are capable of being characterized and stably propagated over a period of time. A *new* cell line can be "established" not only through the passaging/selection of a primary culture
column5: but also through experimental modifications of existing lines (e.g. immortalization
column7: drug selection for a resistant subset
column8: etc.).  As defined here
column9: 'cell line' can refer to a population of cells in active culture
column11: or stored in a quescent state for future use.

"label": 2. The definitional criteria provided here for the 'cell line' class demarcates populations that represent what researchers actually use in the practice of science - e.g. as inputs to culturing
"rel": and sharing. The definition is such that cell lines will exhibit important attributes. For example
"ent2": they will have a relatively homogenous cell type composition as they have experienced similar selective pressures due to their continuous co-propagation. In addition
column5: these populations can also be characterized by a passage number
column6: again owing to their common passaging history.?

"label": 3. Definitinal criteria are intended to be sufficiently clear to specify what are and what are not instances of 'cell lines' in the real world. A 'HeLa cell line' would be a subset of all HeLa cells in the world - specifically any subset that has been derived through a shared continuous lineage wherein the cells have always been passaged together and thereby evolved together through the selective pressures imposed by this common history. Accordingly
"ent1": 'HeLa cell line' would not be used to refer to the collection of all HeLa cells in a given lab
"rel": or all HeLa cells in the ATCC repository
"ent2": as cells in these collections will likely not all share a common culture history. Rather
column5: 'HeLa cell line' could refer to the collection of cells I am culturing at a given moment
column6: or that I apply in an experiment (as such collections typically meet the criteria of having a shared propagation history).  As noted above
column7: it is such collections that are typically referred to in scientific discourse and publications.

"ent1": the term 'line' has been alternately used by other terminologies and communities to refer to cultures that have been immortalized - ie has attained the capacity for indefinite propagation in vitro.  In this ontology
"rel": we refer to such cell lines as 'immortal cell lines'
"ent2": and use the term 'cell line' to indicate any culture that has been passaged."

"label": 2013-6-5 MHB: There is considerable ambiguity and inconsistent usage surrounding the term 'cell line' across biomedical communities. For exmaple
"ent1": it can refer to the maximal collection of all cells in a cultured lineage (e.g. the colelction of all HeLa cells that exist)
"rel": or to discrete portions of this maximal collection that are stored
column5: and applied experimentally (e.g. the dish of HeLa cells I am using in my experiment). A working group of representatives from OBI
column7: and CL was assembled in spring of 2013 to harmonize modeling and terminology surrounding experimentally cultured cells across Open Biomedical Ontologies
column8: following OBO Foundry principles of orthogonality and re-use. A consensus was reached to apply the term 'cell line' to refer not to a maximal collection of cells of a given type
column9: but to discrete populations of cultured cells that share a common propagation history which has conferred a certain a genetic stability and compositional homogeneity to the population.  This meaning reflects its most common usage in domain discourse
column10: and will best support data annotation requirements. This view means that a 'HeLa cell line' would be a subset of all HeLa cells in the world - specifically any subset that has been derived through a shared continuous lineage wherein the cells have always been passaged together and thereby evolved together through the selective pressures imposed by this specific history. Accordingly
column11: 'HeLa cell line' would not be used to refer to collections such as all HeLa cells in a given lab
column12: or all HeLa cells in the ATCC repository
column13: as all cells in these collections do not necessarily share a common culture history. Rather
column14: it could be used to refer to the collection of cells I am culturing at a given moment
column15: or that I apply in an experiment (as such collections typically meet the criteria of having a shared propagation history).

"label": This approach seems to accomplish several desirable goals:
1) It allows us to define the term 'cell line' for the community in a precise way that also reflects how the term is most commonly used in the literature and scientific discourse.
(2) It gives a definition that provides clear criteria to help specify what are and what are not instances of 'cell lines' in the real world
(3) The criteria it provides demarcate populations that represent what researchers actually use in the practice of science - ie are the inputs to culturing
"rel": and sharing. The cells in such populations will be a relatively uniform population as they have experienced similar selective pressures due to their continuous co-propagation. And this population will also have a single passage number
"ent2": again owing to their common passaging history.

"label": (4) The definition seems to be true to the meaning of the word 'line' - which is suggests a specific lineage of derivation."

"label": "1. The term 'line' is used when a culture has undergone an intentional experimental process to establish a more uniform and stable population of cells (see 'establishing cell line'). This will require one or more passages
"ent1": but may involve additional selection processes. Through such passaging and/or selection processes
"rel": the resulting 'line' attains some level of genetic stability and compositional homogeneity which is typically absent in primary cultures. Because of their relative homogeneity
"ent2": 'lines' are capable of being characterized and stably propagated over a period of time. A *new* cell line can be "established" not only through the passaging/selection of a primary culture
column5: but also through experimental modifications of existing lines (e.g. immortalization
column7: drug selection for a resistant subset
column8: etc.).  As defined here
column9: 'cell line' can refer to a population of cells in active culture
column11: or stored in a quescent state for future use.

"label": 2. The definitional criteria provided here for the 'cell line' class demarcates populations that represent what researchers actually use in the practice of science - e.g. as inputs to culturing
"rel": and sharing. The definition is such that cell lines will exhibit important attributes. For example
"ent2": they will have a relatively homogenous cell type composition as they have experienced similar selective pressures due to their continuous co-propagation. In addition

column6: again owing to their common passaging history.?

"label": 3. Definitinal criteria are intended to be sufficiently clear to specify what are and what are not instances of 'cell lines' in the real world. A 'HeLa cell line' would be a subset of all HeLa cells in the world - specifically any subset that has been derived through a shared continuous lineage wherein the cells have always been passaged together and thereby evolved together through the selective pressures imposed by this common history. "ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"label": ""Soil Erosion is a common term that is often confused with soil degradation as a whole
"ent1": but in fact refers only to absolute soil losses in terms of topsoil and nutrients. This  is indeed the most visible effect of soil degradation
"rel": but does not cover all of its aspects. Soil erosion is a natural process in mountainous areas
"ent2": but is often made much worse by poor management practices." http://www.fao.org/soils-portal/soil-degradation-restoration/en/"

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

column5: "A mangrove biome is a terrestrial biome which includes
column7: mangrove plants (Rhizophoraceae). Mangrove plants are able to withstand high levels of salinity as well as regions of anoxia and frequent tidal inundation. Mangrove biomes often occur near tropical and sub-tropical estuaries and depositional marine coastal environments where fine sediments (often with high organic content) collect in areas protected from high energy wave action."

Reagents are distinguished from instruments or devices that also participate in scientific techniques by the fact that reagents are chemical or biological in nature and necessarily participate in or have parts that participate in some chemical interaction or reaction during their intended participation in some technique.  By contrast
"ent1": instruments do not participate in a chemical reaction/interaction during the technique.

"label": Reagents are distinguished from study subjects/evaluants in that study subjects and evaluants are that about which conclusions are drawn and knowledge is sought in an investigation - while reagents
"rel": are not.  It should be noted
column5: that reagent and study subject/evaluant roles can be borne by instances of the same type of material entity - but a given instance will realize only one of these roles in the execution of a given assay or technique. For example
column6: taq polymerase can bear a reagent role or an evaluant role.  In a DNA sequencing assay aimed at generating sequence data about some plasmid
column7: the reagent role of the taq polymerase is realized. In an assay to evaluate the quality of the taq polymerase itself
column8: the evaluant/study subject role of the taq is realized
column9: but not the reagent role since the taq is the subject about which data is generated.

"label": In regard to the statement that reagents are 'distinct' from the specified outputs of a technique
"ent1": note that a reagent may be incorporated into a material output of a technique
"rel": as long as the IDENTITY of this output is distinct from that of the bearer of the reagent role.  For example
"ent2": dNTPs input into a PCR are reagents that become part of the material output of this technique
column5: but this output has a new identity (ie that of a 'nucleic acid molecule') that is distinct from the identity of the dNTPs that comprise it.  Similarly
column6: a biotin molecule input into a cell labeling technique are reagents that become part of the specified output
column7: but the identity of the output is that of some modified cell specimen which shares identity with the input unmodified cell specimen
column8: and not with the biotin label. Thus
column9: we see that an important criteria of 'reagent-ness' is that it is a facilitator
column10: and not the primary focus of an investigation or material processing technique (ie not the specified subject/evaluant about which knowledge is sought
column11: or the specified output material of the technique)."

"label": May 28 2013. Updated definition taken from ReO based on discussions initiated in Philly 2011 workshop.  Former defnition described a narrower view of reagents in chemistry that restricts bearers of the role to be chemical entities ("a role played by a molecular entity used to produce a chemical reaction to detect
"rel": or produce other substances").  Updated definition allows for broader view of reagents in the domain of biomedical research to include larger materials that have parts that participate chemically in a molecular reaction or interaction.

"label": "A 'cell culture' as used here referes to a new lineage of cells in culture deriving from a single biological source.. New cultures are established through the initial isolation and culturing of cells from an organismal source
"ent1": or through changes in an existing cell culture or line that result in a new culture with unique characteristics.  This can occur through the passaging/selection of a primary culture into a secondary culture or line
"rel": or experimental modifications of an existing cell culture or line such as an immortalization process or other stable genetic modification. This class covers establishment of cultures of either multicellular organism cells or unicellular organisms."

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. "ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"As with most other climatic zones and conditions
"ent1": multiple classification schemes have somehat different definitions and criteria. To quote from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ "Several methods have been used to define the subtropical climate. In the Trewartha climate classification
"rel": a subtropical region should have at least eight months with a mean temperature of 10 °C (50.0 °F) or above. German climatologists Carl Troll and Karlheinz Paffen defined Warm temperate zones as plain and hilly lands having an average temperature of the coldest month between 2 °C (35.6 °F) and 13 °C (55.4 °F) in the Northern Hemisphere and between 6 °C (42.8 °F) and 13 °C (55.4 °F) in the Southern Hemisphere
"ent2": excluding oceanic and continental climates. According to the Troll-Paffen climate classification
column5: there generally exists one large subtropical zone named the warm-temperate subtropical zone
column6: [4] which is subdivided into seven smaller areas.[5]

"label": According to the E. Neef climate classification

"rel": the subtropical zone is divided into three parts: high-continental
column5: and maritime.[7] According to the Siegmund/Frankenberg climate classification
column6: subtropical is one of six climate zones in the world.[8]""

"label": "Debate exists whether a wet meadow is a type of marsh or a completely separate type of wetland. Wet prairies and wet savannas are hydrologically similar. Wet meadows may occur because of restricted drainage or the receipt of large amounts of water from rain or melted snow. They may also occur in riparian zones and around the shores of large lakes. Unlike a marsh or swamp
"ent1": a wet meadow does not have standing water present except for brief to moderate periods during the growing season. Instead
"rel": the ground in a wet meadow fluctuates between brief periods of inundation and longer periods of saturation. Wet meadows often have large numbers of wetland plant species
"ent2": which frequently survive as buried seeds during dry periods
column5: and then regenerate after flooding. Wet meadows therefore do not usually support aquatic life such as fish. They typically have a high diversity of plant species
column6: and may attract large numbers of birds
column7: small mammals and insects including butterflies."
column8: "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000154"
column9: "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf"

Reagents are distinguished from instruments or devices that also participate in scientific techniques by the fact that reagents are chemical or biological in nature and necessarily participate in or have parts that participate in some chemical interaction or reaction during their intended participation in some technique.  By contrast
"ent1": instruments do not participate in a chemical reaction/interaction during the technique.

"label": Reagents are distinguished from study subjects/evaluants in that study subjects and evaluants are that about which conclusions are drawn and knowledge is sought in an investigation - while reagents
"rel": are not.  It should be noted
column5: that reagent and study subject/evaluant roles can be borne by instances of the same type of material entity - but a given instance will realize only one of these roles in the execution of a given assay or technique. For example
column6: taq polymerase can bear a reagent role or an evaluant role.  In a DNA sequencing assay aimed at generating sequence data about some plasmid
column7: the reagent role of the taq polymerase is realized. In an assay to evaluate the quality of the taq polymerase itself
column8: the evaluant/study subject role of the taq is realized
column9: but not the reagent role since the taq is the subject about which data is generated.

"label": In regard to the statement that reagents are 'distinct' from the specified outputs of a technique
"ent1": note that a reagent may be incorporated into a material output of a technique
"rel": as long as the IDENTITY of this output is distinct from that of the bearer of the reagent role.  For example
"ent2": dNTPs input into a PCR are reagents that become part of the material output of this technique
column5: but this output has a new identity (ie that of a 'nucleic acid molecule') that is distinct from the identity of the dNTPs that comprise it.  Similarly
column6: a biotin molecule input into a cell labeling technique are reagents that become part of the specified output
column7: but the identity of the output is that of some modified cell specimen which shares identity with the input unmodified cell specimen
column8: and not with the biotin label. Thus
column9: we see that an important criteria of 'reagent-ness' is that it is a facilitator
column10: and not the primary focus of an investigation or material processing technique (ie not the specified subject/evaluant about which knowledge is sought
column11: or the specified output material of the technique)."

"rel": are not.  It should be noted
column5: that reagent and study subject/evaluant roles can be borne by instances of the same type of material entity - but a given instance will realize only one of these roles in the execution of a given assay or technique. For example
column6: taq polymerase can bear a reagent role or an evaluant role.  In a DNA sequencing assay aimed at generating sequence data about some plasmid
column7: the reagent role of the taq polymerase is realized. In an assay to evaluate the quality of the taq polymerase itself
column8: the evaluant/study subject role of the taq is realized
column9: but not the reagent role since the taq is the subject about which data is generated.

"label": In regard to the statement that reagents are 'distinct' from the specified outputs of a technique
"ent1": note that a reagent may be incorporated into a material output of a technique
"rel": as long as the IDENTITY of this output is distinct from that of the bearer of the reagent role.  For example
"ent2": dNTPs input into a PCR are reagents that become part of the material output of this technique
column5: but this output has a new identity (ie that of a 'nucleic acid molecule') that is distinct from the identity of the dNTPs that comprise it.  Similarly
column6: a biotin molecule input into a cell labeling technique are reagents that become part of the specified output
column7: but the identity of the output is that of some modified cell specimen which shares identity with the input unmodified cell specimen
column8: and not with the biotin label. Thus
column9: we see that an important criteria of 'reagent-ness' is that it is a facilitator
column10: and not the primary focus of an investigation or material processing technique (ie not the specified subject/evaluant about which knowledge is sought
column11: or the specified output material of the technique)."

"label": Reagents are distinguished from study subjects/evaluants in that study subjects and evaluants are that about which conclusions are drawn and knowledge is sought in an investigation - while reagents

column5: that reagent and study subject/evaluant roles can be borne by instances of the same type of material entity - but a given instance can only realize one of these roles in the execution of a given  assay. For example

The extent of the collection of cells in a 'secondary cultured cell population' is restricted only in that all cell members must share a propagation history (ie be derived through a common lineage of passages from an initial culture).  Secondary cultured cell populations can be under active culture

"label": "A 'cell culture' as used here referes to a new lineage of cells in culture deriving from a single biological source.. New cultures are established through the initial isolation and culturing of cells from an organismal source
"ent1": or through changes in an existing cell culture or line that result in a new culture with unique characteristics.  This can occur through the passaging/selection of a primary culture into a secondary culture or line
"rel": or experimental modifications of an existing cell culture or line such as an immortalization process or other stable genetic modification. This class covers establishment of cultures of either multicellular organism cells or unicellular organisms."

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. "label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

"label":
The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.

The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm.  Soil taxonomy

"ent1": soil is referred to as regolith
"rel": or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically
"ent2": the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil

Reagents are distinguished from instruments or devices that also participate in scientific techniques by the fact that reagents are chemical or biological in nature and necessarily participate in or have parts that participate in some chemical interaction or reaction during their intended participation in some technique.  By contrast
"ent1": instruments do not participate in a chemical reaction/interaction during the technique.

"label": Reagents are distinguished from study subjects/evaluants in that study subjects and evaluants are that about which conclusions are drawn and knowledge is sought in an investigation - while reagents
"rel": are not.  It should be noted
column5: that reagent and study subject/evaluant roles can be borne by instances of the same type of material entity - but a given instance will realize only one of these roles in the execution of a given assay or technique. For example
column6: taq polymerase can bear a reagent role or an evaluant role.  In a DNA sequencing assay aimed at generating sequence data about some plasmid
column7: the reagent role of the taq polymerase is realized. In an assay to evaluate the quality of the taq polymerase itself
column8: the evaluant/study subject role of the taq is realized
column9: but not the reagent role since the taq is the subject about which data is generated.

"label": In regard to the statement that reagents are 'distinct' from the specified outputs of a technique
"ent1": note that a reagent may be incorporated into a material output of a technique
"rel": as long as the IDENTITY of this output is distinct from that of the bearer of the reagent role.  For example
"ent2": dNTPs input into a PCR are reagents that become part of the material output of this technique
column5: but this output has a new identity (ie that of a 'nucleic acid molecule') that is distinct from the identity of the dNTPs that comprise it.  Similarly
column6: a biotin molecule input into a cell labeling technique are reagents that become part of the specified output
column7: but the identity of the output is that of some modified cell specimen which shares identity with the input unmodified cell specimen
column8: and not with the biotin label. Thus
column9: we see that an important criteria of 'reagent-ness' is that it is a facilitator
column10: and not the primary focus of an investigation or material processing technique (ie not the specified subject/evaluant about which knowledge is sought
column11: or the specified output material of the technique)."

"label": "A 'cell culture' as used here referes to a new lineage of cells in culture deriving from a single biological source.. New cultures are established through the initial isolation and culturing of cells from an organismal source
"ent1": or through changes in an existing cell culture or line that result in a new culture with unique characteristics.  This can occur through the passaging/selection of a primary culture into a secondary culture or line
"rel": or experimental modifications of an existing cell culture or line such as an immortalization process or other stable genetic modification. This class covers establishment of cultures of either multicellular organism cells or unicellular organisms."
